comments_1: Thank You

This is my fourth time in the program, and all of the staff are so wonderful! From the front desk staff, to therapists/psychologists and psychiatrists. Through zoom you all still create such a welcoming environment!! This program has saved my life many times, and for that I am forever grateful. Shout out to Dr.Doug for being one of the best BEAR group leaders!  Things I recommend for the program are more male therapists in the trauma track, it is life changing when you're fear of men is challenged in that way. Im going to miss the support, but happy I get to start life again. Thank you all!!!
I felt really supported by not only the staff members but also the other members in the program. Everyone wants the best for each other and it gives a welcoming and caring feel.
Thank You

I entered The program because hope led to dispare.  The program gave me the opportunity to make the final step that I was petrified to make ibut needed to make in order to assist in my full recovery. I was blessed to find a  treatment team and doctors that listened to me and saw my abilities and needs  as the individual i am and didnt for a minute try to take the easy way out that doctors In my past had and failed me. We combined our intelligence together to get to the root cause of why I needed the treatment in the first place. Thank You everyone! You know what your doing!

I think it's difficult to rate my satisfaction with the ACT and skills-based groups over the course of three weeks because there's a lot of variation between instructors. I highly appreciated Kristin Davidoff (I believe that was her name) as I felt she was the most relatable. Specifically, her mastery of the material, her ability to communicate and relate to the group, her sense of humor, and the way she spoke (not using an overly neutral, robotic way of speaking that I find many therapists mistakenly feel is best). I also very much appreciated my therapist Cerena and psychiatrist Dr. Fotros. Of special note, I felt that Dr. Fotros' student Collin (can't remember spelling or last name, apologies!) was extremely capable and he filled in for Dr. Fotros on her day off. Thank you for all the work you do. Overall, I think I was in a tough place, and this place did provide me with a sense of connection, structure, and community that I'd been lacking for months.

Sarah Zimage is an amazing therapist! She deserves a raise. She knew exactly what to say to make the therapy session meaningful and productive. Dr. Lahaye was great and very knowledgeable. The clinicians running groups were All Helpful and great at what they do. Thank you everyone.

I am so thankful to the staff of the RI Hospital Partial Inpatient program. Thank you so much for everything you do. I can honestly say that you've all changed my life and I will continue to work hard on the skills I have learned here.
Thank you very much for your help.
Thank you  Unfortunately, still struggling to find the right meds. So, no real improvement in my depression , anxiety, and agoraphobia.
As I've mentioned this before PHP at RIH is by far the best program I've ever experienced and without any hesitation will always refer others to, who are in need.  Thank you to all!
Both my doctor and therapist were extremely helpful for my success in the my progress and growth. I feel very fortunate to have had both of them during such a difficult time in my life!
Dr D'Avanzato and Dr Firman, really helped me work through some of the pain and issues I was dealing with. I wish I could continue treatment with them.

Thank you all infinitely for the guidance, care and extreme compassion I received while in this program. I feel as if you've helped me make monumental strides and have instilled a confidence in me that I hadn't felt in so long. I will miss this program and that alone is a testament to what a great job you're all doing. All the best, Ruby ❤️
Thank you!
Therapists were extremely helpful and opened my eyes up to the issues I was having and the correct paths to work on to clear my head of negative thoughts
Sometimes the ACT group and Coping Skills group were redundant but overall very satisfied with the program. It helped cement many skills that I have came across over the years.
Thank you all for everything. I feel like a newer, better person with a clearer head on their shoulders and coping skills to help me every day. Thank you so much.

I was in this program for just under a month, and am being forced out because of insurance complications. I received a late diagnosis, and barely got any time to work on it before my psychiatrist was saying we should "give it a couple weeks" once my time ended. Now I'm not even sure if I want to return. What's the point? If I knew this program's enrollment was based on strict goals and timelines, I would have never gotten involved. Now my sense of "I'm too much for anyone" in addition to abandonment trauma have been triggered, and I feel worse than ever.
Thank you all
I was really happy and satisfied with the program. Would use it again if needed or highly recommend it to someone else :-)

The groups made me feel worse pretty consistently. I felt like there is a constant over emphasis on individual action and feelings and a total disregard for systemic flaws that cause deaths of despair and suffering,  like fascism,  racism, xenophobia, misogyny, and capitalism. I felt disconnected from the others in the group, like my problems were not real or valid compared to their extreme physical suffering. There was so much I wanted to say but I can't trust public groups that could contain fascists or white supremacists. I think CBT is not helpful for me and seems like a collection of trite worksheets and cheap bodily tricks that want to minimize my pain, tell me I'm not permitted to have emotions like rage or self hate,  control me, and promote an attitude of "fake it till you make it" or "suck it up".     I do not feel any more prepared to cope with going back to work at a job I hate that exacerbates my mental illness... than when I started. I now have the added stress of my father being incredibly sick and having to go back to NJ and expose myself to an environment and people that make me hate myself and self harm. I feel I have basically been told to suck it up or lose my apartment and be homeless. And that's the reality, isn't it? That I just have to suffer. That's life. I shouldn't complain about anything because people in this program are missing legs and have cancer. Is this the "acceptance" you speak of?     I want Dr. Mohindish Shukla, one of the directors of the UMass Baby Lab and professor of psychology at UMass Boston to be fired from his job for anally raping me in 2013. He should never be permitted to work in this field again and I hope that me stating clearly his name and what he did will start the wheels of holding him accountable for his sadism. This would be justice, something which is clearly beyond the program's capacity to provide.     That being said, I am grateful for the time spent with Dr. Meth and Dr. Fotros and my time spent in the program. It was very difficult to get this care and I know space must be made so others can access their services. They are talented professionals and good at their work. I know I am not an easy patient. Dr. Gazarian was also very patient with me. I also truly appreciate the help navigating paperwork and bureaucracy for work and insurance ...which is so overwhelming and unreasonable.     I also wanted to devote a part of this comment section to say how much I appreciate the food delivery. It allowed me one less thing to worry about as I try to heal. It was one small thing that said to me "there are forces in our culture who care about you and want you to survive this". To have delicious free vegetables sent to my home is something I feel SO MUCH GRATITUDE for and I hope the program continues this service. Maslow's hierarchy of needs is real and I can focus on my mental health when I have nutritious delicious food in my body.     Also Sandy and Maria in the office are an absolute blessing to this program and have been kind and helpful during every single interaction I had with them. They deserve a raise.
Thanks for the help everyone! Your work will not you noticed!

I am grateful I was able to participate in this group.  I was impressed by all the professionals.  I can't help but wonder if it would have been more impactful in person but I do feel that I got a lot out of it anyway.

I am really grateful to this program, I think there is an environment of care and belief that people can be helped that really allowed me to fully participate and not doubt as much as I normally do if i should be here or not. Thank you!

I am EXTREMELY grateful to Dr. Zimmerman, my psychiatrist, Doug Gazarian, my therapist and the entire psych team and admin staff for the critical help and support you have provided to me during my battles with mental health since 2015. Each visit has not only helped save my life but restored my faith in huMANity (family of origin reference joke :) Thank you for always helping me in my worst crisis and for being the soft place to land to get back to my healthy self again.  Soooo appreciate all of you and what you do especially with ACT and mindfulness training.  Thank you all again so very much!!  With gratitude always,  Maureen R

1. Did not receive the binder until the end, that would have been very helpful.  2. Too many changes of group leaders with all the groups, never felt like I got comfortable with them or with participants. I felt uncomfortable talking in the groups because of this.  3. Group leaders should incorporate more learning modalities- too much talking- I suggest Google Slide presentations. Try to use different learning pathways- auditory, visual, kinesthetic. Not everyone can learn by mainly listening.  4. Interpersonal group is TOO LONG.  5.Include a break in the middle with physical movement such as tai chi or yoga. It is far too sedentary.  6.Show videos during groups that support the teaching- i.e. meditation etc.  7. Start each group by identifying the TOPIC of the day. This was not done in most sessions and lead to confusion. Give the daily objective at the outset.  8. Many times it felt like the group leader was not very prepared. Just typing as you go instead of having prepared slides. Some were more prepared than others.   9.Not everyone is comfortable being seen on camera. I felt micromanaged on this aspect. It made me uncomfortable.  10. At the outset, I called up to ask if I could have a more experienced therapist and I never got any assistance or feedback whatsoever to this concern.

I was pleasantly surprised with how much therapy I received during my program.  I was a bit hesitant at first but everyone made me feel welcomed.  I already recommended this program to a couple family members.  Thank you to the entire staff.  :-)
Try not to forget to invite people to the groups please.
See earlier submission

The office staff also were very nice to me when i would bother them with questions. Your staff are what makes the program successful and without them it would not be. I hope you continue to have staff with the doctorate and MD level training coupled with experience. It is what makes your program stand out and be a success to your past consumers. Thanks TA

I am extremely grateful for this program and all that I learned from it.  This has been the most instrumental tool in my lifetime.  Thank you, sincerely.

This Program is a life changing experience all the staff therapist & physiologist are very pleasant and helpful. I am very grateful for this program you guys are doing amazing things ! THANK YOU :)

Would like to thank the entire staff, from Maria, to all of the moderators to Katie and Dr. Moon.  All of them took a genuine interest in my well being.
working 1 on 1 was very beneficial for me.  I do like the groups but the 1 on 1 was extremely helpful.

I would like to see the "Teletherapy" continue  as an available option- post "Covid". Having a medical condition that restricts my ability to get to an on-site program due to weather conditions or other variables, makes it difficult to commit to an in-person program. That said, I feel there is no substitution  for person-person. But making it an option could attract and help more people who need help but can not make it in person.  I would also like to give a "shout out" to Maria whose upbeat personality made me smile- especially during mornings I wasnt so motivated. She cheered me up. Also- sandy was so sweet, helpful and caring. The staff was excellent. Wish I could stay w my Dr and Therapist- as they both were the BEST :) Thank you all for your important and meaningful work.
Thanks to everyone on staff that makes the program so helpful.    And keep up the delicious food from Luigi's!
I have been so surprised at how helpful this program has been.  The skills are wonderfully helpful and participating in interpersonal groups has been life changing.

I would suggest setting a set time everyday from the beginning to meet with psychiatrist/therapist would be helpful. I also felt a bit stressed out and disconnected when I had to leave some of the other sessions to meet with psychiatrist/therapist, especially when I was deeply focused in my group. As a suggestion, maybe it would be best not to allow any outside appts during the interpersonal group timeslot? I think that was when it was most problematic because I was trying to be mindful of time and also be engaged and it was stressful to do that.

I began the program broken and hopeless. At the end I felt the opposite. It was a combination of all the factors. The care by my providers, and the group leaders. And the openness and support of the other participants.  I could not have asked for anything better. I am overwhelmed with gratitude for everything this program did for me, and the contribution of all those involved.
Thank you to everyone who makes this program possible.

Dr. Palermo and Dr. Meth were absolutely wonderful to work with.  The staff overall is fantastic.  It was a pleasure to check in with Maria each morning.  Pleasantly surprised by how beneficial and supportive the daily IPT group was.   Overall very thankful for my time in the program.
Did not believe when I first started that this was going to be worth anything. I was totally wrong it's an excellent program. Thank you for helping me as much as you could

While I understand that the interpersonal group is a time for people to share, I wonder if perhaps people should have time limits when speaking as certain group members would talk for the entirety of the hour and a half session and left little room for others to share their issues that day.

I got hardly any proteins in my vegetarian meals, and I had to ask about every week for it to be delivered to the right door or before I went to work, or to get something really vegetarian. I share a fridge so it was not great to expect food and not get any, or to shop because I can't rely on this delivery like everyone else and then have too much food for my fridge. Then I had to deal with Maria in the check in. She never gave me the impression that she cared or was trying. I also don't think she really cared about anything I was saying. She asks everyone 2 times how they are, and gets an attitude if she gets an answer other than "Great!". She tells people she never gets complaints about lunch, but Maria, I'm real and I complain at least once a week. She's also obsessed with hump day and friday/the weekend and gives the impression that she hates her job. I think then she should get a new one. I work also, and I am expected to behave in a considerate way.
My psychiatrist was wonderful but I probably didn't need to have as many session simply because I was on medication coming into the program and  what I needed was a more therapy based approach.

I had a wonderful experience with this program.  I started in a dark place but I was determined to "be me again."  I learned many valuable skills that will be with me the rest of my life.  The 1:1 sessions with my therapist were invaluable.  I had a safe, confidential environment where I bared my soul. She gave me insights that helped me understand and realize that my thoughts and feelings were legitimate and she helped me refocus them in a healthy light.  She also helped me get rid of ones that were not good for me and keeping me in a dark place.  Every day I would write down a "take away" from one part of the day.  It was always an aha moment that made sense to me in my journey to get "better".  I read it ever day.    From first thing in the morning when I had to check in, Maria was there with a smile on her face and an up beat attitude asking how I was doing.  It was a positive way to start my day."Thank you Maria!!"  The only hard part was listening to the folks in the group session.  Some of them have such heart wrenching stories that I felt I should go hide in a corner.  But anxiety and depression are not things to shrug off no matter where they come from so when I accepted that I could listen better.     I feel the program gave me my life back and a huge thank-you to all that helped me get there.  Sincerely, Joan B

Thank you. At my initial intake I was told to delete daily emails to avoid confusion. If I had followed that advice, I would not have been able to Zoom with my psychiatrist because she only sent one initial email, in total. I am in college (remotely) and am very familiar with Zoom/email/telemedicine; I imagine it would be much more challenging for an elderly patient or someone less familiar with the technology. Definitely could be an information overload for an anxious person -- at least it was for me, at times. Otherwise, great staff and program. Stay safe and keep up the good work!

I've personally given Geren credit to her, where credit is DEFINITELY due!!!    She was absolutely amazing and has made me think in such a different manner.  Her supervisor should know, please!!   Also, Dr. Fotros, I can't thank her enough either, and wish I said more during our last session.  Dr. Fotros, has such a warm heart, genuine manner, and is SMART AS HELL!  I really appreciate the constructive criticism, as well as the positive feedback, that she provided to me.  Seeing a Psychiatrist, as I had the great opportunity to work with Dr. Fotros, was such a different and positive experience for me.  I really like that she'd also give me things to think about in different aspects.  She also went above and beyond by making a huge connection with me, and actually asked about favorite song(s), and took the time to listen to them.   How many Doctors really do that?  Her mannerisms clearly show that she is just "smooth" and easy mannered with approach.  And, each and every time we met, she was 100% consistent each time, which means a lot.  Also, teaching a new skill, like Positive Reframing, was really cool, as well as suggesting a Dr. David Burns Ted Talk, which was extremely insightful.  The whole team would benefit from having her share what she's learned from him, while being mentored.  I really appreciate how much time she took with me.  Her creativity is beyond amazing, and it was awesome to get a new approach, as I had with the treatment team I had during this admission.  Also, I've been a witness to the lucky students who were also working on my team, ALL - with my well-being a priority.  The students I got to meet in the past month, under Dr. Fotros' lead, WILL DEFINITELY leave their experience during their time at the program, with a huge boatload of knowledge, I know I've gobbled up from her, and those were with just my interactions alone.  I can't imagine what everyone else thinks.  Thank you, to everyone!  Especially though Dr. Fotros and Geren, because they both knew the potential challenges they may have faced with the tendency to resist change, especially with providers.  However, working with Dr. Fotros from day 1, I knew she'd be a great fit for me, during my stay this time around.  Umm, the other key thing too about Dr. Fotros, is she's on top of her game!  She cares and it showed, by taking care of any medication refills I knew were coming and she took care of them right away.  I didn't even know she had done this, and still called me back directly on her own to let me know.   I'm really in hopes she gets this direct feedback as well.  She really deserves to be recognized for all that she does, and for being a huge asset to The Partial Hospital Program!      The appreciation cannot be expressed enough, for the program itself overall.  I've said this time and time again, after the admissions I've had since 2015.  This is definitely the best day program I've ever been to.  It also just keeps getting better and better.    As much as I would not care to be back in the program, I'd love to be able to just observe and watch how much more the program will grow.    Let's face it, the front desk... also needs to be recognized.  Especially, Maria!  She certainly deserves credit where credit is due as well.  I'm not too sure I've ever even got to express this, I won't let it slip by this time, if I've missed her before.  Maria, you can't be thanked enough either.  To see you first thing in the morning, before a long day of hard work, is the best thing ever.  Your personality glows and you are absolutely beyond caring, least to say.  Maria, please...keep doing what you do.  I can feel the warmness from you, while waiting for your turn during check in.  The process was so easy and taken care of quickly, which is amazing because overall, there's got to be so many people checking in from 8/8:30, handling calls, helping others...blows my mind!  If it were my first time to the program, I'd be put so at least ease with my first part of the day with someone who just shines right on up there, with the stars!!  Thanks Maria!     Again, thank you all to everyone who was a part of my care since November.  I TRULY and sincerely am giving my heartfelt thank you once again.  Be safe and well.  Wishing everyone a great, 2021!!    Jess (I don't mind not being anonymous)
Thank you for the healing of unconditional positive regard from all concerned and the deep and helpful insights from the staff.

I didn't know what to expect going in and had a nervewracking first day but my individual providers were very approachable and were wonderful throughout the duration of the program. I felt I had a comfortable space here and enjoyed the structure it gave my life, even if by the end I felt quite drained by the repetitiveness that comes with intensive outpatient.    The ability to meet with my individual providers daily was key; I could express day to day anxieties that came up out of the treatment process itself, and I felt that anything I encountered was manageable because I didn't have to go think it through alone. At the same time, my psychologist has been able to help me tackle the mental barriers that stand between me and my independence, something I still have a long road ahead with, but I've had it proved to me that I'm capable of making that progress.    I had my original discharge date planned a bit earlier but it was suggested to me that I continue for a few more days since the end of my stay coincided with the passing of a grandparent, which also brought back some conflict with my parents; this was a great call and I'm thankful that the program coordinated that, because had it not been recommended to me I would have gone along with the original discharge as planned without a proper sense of readiness.    I'm glad that I've reached my discharge date although I will miss the support from this specific program. Knowing that I can return in the future with (potentially) the same individual providers if I fall back into a bad place is reassuring, but I hope I never have to. Overall I found this program really helpful and I was impressed by the amount of transparent communication as well as how quickly changes to my treatment could be made, especially in regards to medication changes.    Maybe less importantly, the fact that the program delivers lunch to patients is incredible and I really appreciated it, although toward the end I had to cancel receiving it because I was receiving meals at a rate I could not finish.    I'm not sure who reads this survey response but either way, I feel unable to fully express the gratitude I have for the support the providers of this program have given me, and their ability to set me on a better path that I feel confident in. Thank you!!!

I want to extend my thanks to all the providers and staff who work so hard at maintaining such a high quality program... especially in light of these challenging Covid times.  With deepest gratitude for all you do, Kerri
The food is not the best

I do have some constructive feedback that I would love to give. I'll preface by saying that I am so grateful for this program and I'm in a much better place now than I was when I began. I loved the therapist and psychiatrist as well as the staff that led groups.  However I have some issues I feel a need to address because there have been rules that seem questionable for a mental health establishment.   For one thing, the rule that if you miss the 8:30 check-in time you cannot participate.   While maybe this would make sense for a job or school, etc. It feels very backwards for a program about mental health. IE. I slept through my alarm and was told at 9:40 (before any sessions had even begun) that I would not be able to participate. Luckily I've developed some skills in self advocating and with some prodding she said she'd ask my providers who ended up letting me in. My providers were insistent that if it happens again I would miss the entire day because it's a rule of the program. I Ask that you read my reasoning with understanding and I hope you can consider changing this rule.    	For one thing, when I started this program I was told if I did not show up they would call me, then my emergency contacts, and if there were no respondents the police. To be honest this did feel unsettling about the police. My initial response was I'm glad I'm white, as there have been black men, Walter Wallace for example, who was shot and killed while having a bi-polar manic episode by the police. I was unsettled by the strictness, however what I experienced was the quite the opposite extreme. When I failed to check in, I received no calls, not to my personal or extended contacts and the police sure did not knock on my door. So for a mental health establishment who helps people with suicidal ideation and a plethora of mental illnesses, I found this rather shocking. The day that I was told to "take the day off" was the day I needed the program the most. I strongly encourage this rule to be changed or modified. Thank you for hearing what I have to say, I hope it is not taken lightly.
